Aleiodes rugulosus

is a very colour-variable species; the 1st and 2nd metasomal tergites are quite frequently mostly or entirely dark red or orange brown (Fig. 
701
) in populations in which entirely black females (Fig. 
717
) also often occur. The variation is not geographical, since most populations definitely have both forms. In rearing experiments, a strong genetic basis for this feature became evident: from a virgin female with completely black metasoma, all five males reared were black, and a cross between one of them and a (wild-reared) black female produced eleven female progeny, all black. In contrast, a lineage from a pairing between a weakly red male and a red female comprised three red males and eight red females, separate individuals of which produced a single red and a single black male as progeny. When sufficient material from single sites is available it is usual to see a clear predominance of one form or the other. Sometimes the lower part of mesopleuron is pale (often looking unpigmented there, but narrowly), and in extreme reddish specimens the scutellum, much of the mesopleuron (but usually the mesosternum remains darkish), the metanotum dorsally, the metapleuron in part and much of the propodeum are also reddish.
